    "opinion": "As a mechanic living in Milan, I've seen how stereotypes can affect people's confidence and performance, even though I don't work in STEM fields myself. From what I understand, stereotype threat is when someone feels anxious or worried that they might confirm a negative stereotype about their group, like women being told they're not good at math or certain ethnic groups being told they're not cut out for science. This anxiety can actually make them perform worse, creating a self-fulfilling prophecy. I think we should definitely address this because it's unfair and wasteful. When people are held back by stereotypes rather than their actual abilities, we all lose out on potential talent and innovation. In my own life, I've seen how assumptions about my education level or background have affected how people treat me, even though I've developed good mechanical skills through hands-on experience. To address stereotype threat in STEM, I believe we need practical approaches. First, we should create more inclusive environments where everyone feels welcome and judged on their actual work, not stereotypes. This means having diverse role models in STEM fields who can show that anyone can succeed regardless of background. Second, we should focus on mentoring and support systems, especially for young people who might be doubting themselves because of stereotypes. In my community, I've seen how having someone believe in you can make all the difference. Third, we need to be careful about how we talk about abilities, emphasizing that skills in STEM can be developed with effort rather than being something you're just born with or without. As someone with anxiety myself, I know how much negative thoughts can affect performance, so creating supportive, low-pressure learning and work environments seems crucial. Finally, we should collect data to understand where these stereotypes are having the biggest impact and track progress in reducing them. This isn't about giving anyone special treatment, but about making sure everyone has a fair chance to contribute based on their actual capabilities. In my view, addressing stereotype threat is simply about being fair and making the best use of everyone's potential, which benefits society as a whole.",
